@node aboutprefs "About the preferences"
DePack!   can  be configured via several preferences.  They concern a broad
variety of settings e.g.  the needed paths or if you want DePack!  to react
on diskchange-events while depacking the files.

The  preferences  can  be  changed  through two menu selections in the pre-
ferences window

	@{" Edit Preferences " link iprefs} puts up the main prefs window
	@{" Mode             " link mprefs} sets the mode of processing

	@{" Load             " link lprefs} loads new settings from disk
	@{" Save             " link sprefs} saves current settings as default
	@{" Save as          " link aprefs} saves current settings in file

You  can  save  those  settings like normal AmigaDos-preferences and
load them in an later session.  On startup DePack!  tries to use the
preferences  stored  in  a the file 'env:DePack!.prefs'.  If its not
there  the  program  switches back to its internal default settings.
@endnode

@node iprefs "Global Preferences"
A  window will open with many string gadgets in it :  you can change
the  preferences  here.  To understand this you should have read the
introduction of the {@"'DePack!-process'" processing} before.

The  first  nine  boxes  on the left side build the interface to the
external  commands.   They will be used as follows.  If you selected
the  menu-item  @{"Mode/DePack! " link mprefs}.  DePack!  analyses
the files in the source-directories their type.  In 95% of all cases
they can be recognised as 'DMS','LHa', ...  all the other files that
can't be matched need to be specified by you. Here you can determine
in  which  way  those  file are treated.  For every file an external
command  according  to your preferences will be called.  So you have
to  enter  the  commandlines  (the  ones you'd normally enter in the
CLI/Shell)  and  replace  the source name by %s, and the destination
name by %d. For example if the CLI normal commandline you'd normally
use from the Shell would look like this :

	c:dms write bbs:conf1/upload/test.dms drive=df0:

the corresponding line in the preferences would be :

	c:dms write %s drive=%d

The letters %s and %d will be replaced by the correct paths later on
(see below).

In  the  three  uppermost  boxes  on  the  right  side  you have the
possibility  to  enter  one  or  more source-directories.  In one of
those  you  can  specify  where  the  files  to be processed reside.
DePack!  will scan them in the order 1, 2, 3.

The  box  below  contains  the  destination  directory.  The %d (see
above) is to be replaced by this string or, if you are in copy mode.
The files will be copied to this destination-directory.

The  next string gadget determine the /X-directory file to be worked
on.   If  select  a  new  file,  it will be loaded after closing the
window with the close-gadget.

The last 5 gadgets can be easily operated by a file-requester if you
press the button labled 'Get' next to the boxes.

If  the  first  on/off-gadget called 'Detect Diskchange' is selected
DePack!        will       detect      diskchanges      when      the
'Process|...|Skip|Abort'-requester    is    on   screen   and   will
automagically  satisfy the requester if a disk is inserted in one of
the  drives.   (Be  careful  !) This feature doesn't know about your
destination ...  this can cause unwanted writes in certain cases but
normally this should be no problem.

The  one  labeled  'Skip  Unknown'  tells  DePack!   how to react on
unknown  filetypes.   If  it  is selected the program will skip this
ones  otherwise you will be asked to determine the file by yourself.

Number  three  called  'Output'  determines  if  the  output  of the
executed program is sent to a console window or to NIL:

When the last one named 'Immediate Start' is selected the processing
of the files will start immediatly after you selected the menu item,
so  you  needn't  to  press the 'Start/Stop'-gadget.  You don't need
this  option,  but  it  becomes  quit handy if you scan through some
textfiles etc. by selecting only one file a time.
@endnode

@node mprefs "Modes of operation"
DePack! can distinguish between 3 modes of operation :

Mode		Function


DePack		Uses external commands like lha etc. for unpacking
		the sourcefiles.

Copy		Copies the selected files to the destination directory

Delete		Deletes the stuff from the source directories
@endnode

@node lprefs "Load Preferences"
A  file  requester  pops  up  and  you can choose a previously saved
DePack!-preferences  file to load.  If you have selected entries you
need  to confirm that you are willing to load newprefs and thereby a
new AmiX-directory file

!!! MENU ONLY PRESENT IN REGISTERED VERSION !!!
@endnode

@node sprefs "Save Preferences as default"
Save  the  preferences  from  the  preferences  window  to  the file
'ENVARC:DePack!.prefs'.   This is the file DePack!  tries to open on
startup.  If it's found and valid, the program will use the settings
stored in there.

!!! MENU ONLY PRESENT IN REGISTERED VERSION !!!
@endnode

@node aprefs "Save Preferences into file"
A  file  requester  pops up and you are asked to enter a filename in
which  the actual preferences will be saved.  You can load this file
in  a  later  session  with  the  Preferences/@{"Load"  line lprefs}
command.   WARNING  :   This  will  only  save  the  contents of the
preferences  window!   Any  file  selection of yours won't be saved!

!!! MENU ONLY PRESENT IN REGISTERED VERSION !!!
@endnode

